Title: Men, Women & Children International TRAILER (2014) - Ansel Elgort, Jason Reitman Movie HD
Comment: This really is a brilliant movie! Depressing in one way in showing how shallow and spoiled technology has made us. Yet, also uplifting that it can unite people who really need to talk to one another. Somewhat like a Desmond Morris/Nat Geo documentary with the narrative voice over for the first part. And needs to be seen on a large screen or up close to catch all the text messages that appear on screen. But all in all, whether one's up on all this internet hoopla, modern lingo and acronyms or not, it's a thoroughly insightful movie. Pulling no punches on sexual desires and failures, the fragility of emotions, and the dark paths we all take trying to 'fit in' with everyone around us. Much respect for Jason Reitman on this one, and I think Marshall McLuhan would approve as well.

Comment: I saw this movie recently and was quite moved by it. I think it explores some key issues that come along with internet use that many people are either not aware of, or do not talk about. They gave each storyline enough time to develop and "conclude" itself. As well, I love how they slightly connect with one another, somehow. It is similar, in a way, to Disconnect, which I saw a few years prior to this movie. They both deal with internet issues and have separate, yet connected, storylines. I feel that you cannot really say one is "better" than the other, because the issues explored in both are quite different and important on their own. I think everyone should watch both this movie AND Disconnect to get a truly unique experience.

Title: Men, Women & Children International TRAILER (2014) - Ansel Elgort, Jason Reitman Movie HD
Comment: Film is really a triumph in my opinion, I saw it last night on dvd. Adam Sandler is trying to do well in a serious role and he does quite well. The cast is great. This is a film with teen themes without the sentimentality, it's no High School Musical! The pervasive, ubiquitous, invasive role of endless social media and smart phone communication is the subject of this film. The 'world' of the teen is online and any attempt to interfere with this can end in near disastrous consequences. The instantaneous hooking up culture is dealt with as is secrecy: social media means we don't really know what our kids are up to. Real life ('RL') is contrasted to addictive online game-playing, eg the lad who chooses an online set of gamers as pals, while facing the entire opprobrium of his entire school for quitting grid iron football. The consequences of 'raunch' culture is also detailed: the gal who's rejected in the talent quest because she has an overly-explicit online site. 'Cotton wool' parenting is shown in the censorious mom, who over-reaches in her protectiveness and nearly causes fatal results. I was surprised at how moral the film was in its exploration of universal contemporary themes. Good acting all around. A really involving film.

Title: Men, Women & Children International TRAILER (2014) - Ansel Elgort, Jason Reitman Movie HD
Comment:
Just saw this movie! And here's my little review:

I watch many different kinds of movies. I watch anything from science fiction/fantasy, romance, action, horror, etc. But once in a while I like to just turn away from the super hero/fantasy/zombie craze films and just sit down and watch a REAL movie. Not everyday you come across a movie that really makes a huge impact on your life, and what you see from your past and into your future. I just finished watching this movie, and I must say it's one of the most realistic movies of OUR modern times. Nothing in this movie is half-assed, or has any kind of fairy tale ending whatsoever. The movie is basically about how social media/texting are taking over everybody's life, how people seem very artificial nowadays, how many adults cheat, over protectiveness in parents, the dangers of sex in our youth, the significance of life, and the list goes on. In a nutshell this movie is basically about LIFE in our times. This movie is not for everyone, but if you're a deep thinker like me, you'll truly appreciate this film.
